default The WG1 report does not comment on the economic case for action to prevent dangerous climate change and this is outside the regime of expertise of the Royal Meteorological Society.
defaultIs the IPCC process an effective mechanism for assessing scientdefaultific knowledge? Or has it focusdefaulted on providing a justification for political commitment?default1
default6
default. 
defaultWe believe that th
defaulte IPCC process provides a comprehensive, objective, open and transparent
default assessment of the state of scientific knowledge.
default 
defaultWe note that 
defaultthe 
defaultprocess involves
default 
defaulta significant commitment from the scientific community with
default the voluntary contribution of many thousands of scientists worldwide
default. We argue that it is vital that this commitment acts to stimulate scientific research 
defaultrather than placing a burden that may hinder scientific progress
default and that the IPCC process, or a
defaultny modification to 
defaultit, must ensure this.
default 
defaultThe 
defaultIPCC 
defaultreports are neutral with respect to policy
default,
default being policy-relevant but never policy-prescriptive.
default 
defaultBy endorsing the IPCC reports, governments acknowledge the authority of their scientific content.
default 
defaultWhat relevance do the IPCC’s conclusions have in respect of the review of the fourth Carbon Budget? default1
default7
default.
default 
defaultThe report concluded that “Continued emissions of greenhouse gases will cause further warming and changes in all components of the climate system. Limiting climate change will require substantial and sustained reductions of greenhouse gas emissions.” It also concluded “
defaultCumulative emissions of CO2 largely determine global mean surface warming by the late 21st century and beyond. Most aspects of climate change will persist for many centuries even if emissions of CO2 are stopped. This represents a substantial multi-century climate change commitment created by past, present and future emissions of CO2.” We suggest that both these conclusions may be of relevance to the review of the fourth Carbon Budget.
